#Text=Scab in Sheep.
#Text=—For this plague of the graziers a thousand remedies have been suggested, but few have been found efficacious.
#Text=The fallowing recipe ha* recently been tried, with great success, in France.

#Text=Mix a pound of soft soap with four ounces of euphorbium finely powdered ; add enough spirit of turpentine to give the mixture the consistence of pomatum, and hav. ing carefully dipped the wool, anoint the animal every day with the composition.
#Text=By this mods, it it said, a speedy cure may be relied on.
#Text=FAtBS AND MARKETS.
#Text=At Probus fair, on Monday, there was the best supply of fat cattle seen at any fair in this part of the county, for some time.
#Text=The sale, however, was not very brisk ; the prices obtained were from 40s. to 455. pec cwl.
#Text=Sheep went oif heavily at from sjd. to fid. per fl>.
#Text=Truro cattle market, on Wednesday, was well supplied with store cattle, which brought about 30s. per ewl.
#Text=Fat beasts, ofwhicb there was a good supply, sold freely at about 425. per cwt.
#Text=The accounts from Manchester within these few days are of a very gratifying description, A very brisk demand now prevails both for manufactured goods and yams, and prices are somewhat higher.
#Text=Business is also much brisker at Oldham, and the spinners are now pretty generally employed.
#Text=The woollen cloth trade in the West Riding of Yorkshire is greatly improved, but the demand for fancy goods continues dull, and prices Seem unable to get up.

#Text=Our letters from Glasgow speak in favourable terms of the slate of business in that city; and express a confident expectation, that in a very short time, the manufacturers will have little, if any, cause of complaint.
